                    "mention": "[12]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF3"
                }
            ],
            "section": "Introduction to new H7N9 bird flu",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "The signs and symptoms of swine flu are difficult to differentiate from other influenza virus infections. The main clinical signs and symptoms include high fever, coughing and myalgia can be seen[5],[6]. Additional atypical clinical manifestations can also be seen.",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 195,
                    "end": 198,
                    "mention": "[5]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF14"
                },
                {
                    "start": 199,
                    "end": 202,
                    "mention": "[6]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF15"
                }
            ],
            "section": "Laboratory presentations of new H7N9 influenza infection",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "Based on present clinical practice, diagnosis of specific new H7N9 bird flu is totally based on molecular laboratory diagnosis[11],[13]. However, there are also many interesting observation on the routine clinical laboratory investigations.",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 126,
                    "end": 130,
                    "mention": "[11]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF2"
                },
                {
                    "start": 131,
                    "end": 135,
                    "mention": "[13]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF4"
                }
            ],
            "section": "Laboratory presentations of new H7N9 influenza infection",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "Focusing on the routine hematology laboratory testing, complete blood count (CBC), the important observation is on the platelet[5],[6],[14]. Thrombocytopenia is the main platelet disorder. Alteration of thrombohemostasis should be the focus for further hematological study. The other observations on CBC results include leukopenia and lymphopenic[15].",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 127,
                    "end": 130,
                    "mention": "[5]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF14"
                },
                {
                    "start": 131,
                    "end": 134,
                    "mention": "[6]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF15"
                },
                {
                    "start": 135,
                    "end": 139,
                    "mention": "[14]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF5"
                },
                {
                    "start": 346,
                    "end": 350,
                    "mention": "[15]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF6"
                }
            ],
            "section": "Laboratory presentations of new H7N9 influenza infection",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "Focusing on clinical chemistry tests, there are several observations. First, the renal function test can be seen. The impaired renal function reflects the nephrological concern due to H7N9 influenza. Second, the liver function test abnormalities can be seen[15]. The increased level of aminotransferase can be seen and this implies the hepatitis due to the infection[16]. Finally, the increased myocardial enzymes showing cardiac problem can also be seen[15].",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 257,
                    "end": 261,
                    "mention": "[15]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF6"
                },
                {
                    "start": 366,
                    "end": 370,
                    "mention": "[16]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF7"
                },
                {
                    "start": 454,
                    "end": 458,
                    "mention": "[15]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF6"
                }
            ],
            "section": "Laboratory presentations of new H7N9 influenza infection",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "As already mentioned, there are several clinical laboratory aberrations in new emerging H7N9 influenza. This can confirm the observation on multiple organ failure seen in several cases of new H7N9 influenza[5],[6]. Due to the nature of new emerging infections, the nature of atypical laboratory findings can confirm the nature of atypical influenza infections. This might be helpful to a presumptive diagnosis of this newly infection in the period of the outbreak. Any case with clinical feature of classical influenza plus atypical laboratory presentations can lead to the presumptive diagnosis of new H7N9 influenza infection.",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 206,
                    "end": 209,
                    "mention": "[5]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF14"
                },
                {
                    "start": 210,
                    "end": 213,
                    "mention": "[6]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF15"
                }
            ],
            "section": "What learned from laboratory presentations in new H7N9 influneza?",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "Apart from diagnosis usefulness, the basic laboratory investigation can be useful in following up management. Due to the fact that there are many laboratory abnormalities, the investigation can be useful to detect the early problems that help physician in charge plan for proper case management.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "What learned from laboratory presentations in new H7N9 influneza?",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "Nevertheless, further accumulated data is needed. The detected laboratory presentations might be due to other factors, which can be confounding to the presence of H7N9 influenza. Also, the concurrent of other underlying disease such as underlying cardiac diseases, underlying viral hepatitis and underlying blood cytopenia can modify the laboratory finding and severity of the H7N9 influenza infection.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "section": "What learned from laboratory presentations in new H7N9 influneza?",
            "ref_spans": []
        },
        {
            "text": "Due to the nature of new emerging infections, the nature of atypical laboratory findings can confirm the nature of atypical influenza infections[16]\u2013[19].",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 144,
                    "end": 148,
                    "mention": "[16]",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF7"
                },
